With regard to Christian Egypt, we possessed, until lately, no ancient liturgical text which could compare with that of the Syrian Apostolic Constitutions. This want has been supplied by the discovery, in a manuscript at Mount Athos, of a collection of prayers‚ two of which bear the name of Sarapion, Bishop of Thmuis, a friend and correspondent of St. Athanasius.1 1t is probable that the others are of the same authorship. The collection comprises thirty com- positions, connected respectively with the eucharistie liturgy (1-6), with baptism (7-11), with ordination (liz-14), with the blessing of the oils (15-17), with funerals (18), and with the office for Sunday (19-30).
